  "prompt": "What is the proof for triangular law of vectors?",
  "response": "The triangular law of vector addition, also known as the triangle law of vector addition, can be proven geometrically and algebraically. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\nGeometric Proof:\n\n1. Consider two vectors A and B with the same initial point\n\n2. Draw vector A first from the origin\n\n3. Draw vector B from the end point of vector A\n\n4. The resultant vector R will be drawn from the origin to the end point of vector B\n\n5. The magnitude and direction of R can be found by completing the triangle\n\n6. Mathematically, R = A + B\n\nAlgebraic Proof:\n\n1. Let A = (a1, a2) and B = (b1, b2)\n\n2. Resultant vector R = A + B = (a1 + b1, a2 + b2)\n\n3. The magnitude of R can be calculated using the Pythagorean theorem:\n   |R| = \u221a[(a1 + b1)\u00b2 + (a2 + b2)\u00b2]\n\n4. This proves that the triangle formed by the vectors represents their vector sum\n\nKey points:\n- Order of addition doesn't matter\n- Vectors can be translated without changing their properties\n- The resultant follows the triangle law",
